  "prompt": "Is \"A Modest Proposal\" a parody?",
  "response": "Yes, **\"A Modest Proposal\"** by Jonathan Swift is widely regarded as a **parody** and a quintessential example of **satire**. Written in 1729, the essay adopts a serious, rational tone to propose an outrageous solution to poverty and overpopulation in Ireland: suggesting that impoverished Irish families should sell their children as food to the wealthy. Swift\u2019s intent was not to advocate for such a horrifying idea but to use exaggerated and absurd logic to mock and critique the heartless attitudes of the British ruling class toward the Irish poor, as well as the indifference of society to systemic issues.\n\nThe work parodies the style of political and economic pamphlets of the time, which often offered cold, detached solutions to social problems without considering the human cost. Through this biting irony, Swift highlights the absurdity of the conditions and policies that perpetuated suffering in Ireland, making \"A Modest Proposal\" a masterful piece of satirical literature.",
